header.gameNote: MOUNTAIN WEST TR AT DENVER CO

article.headline: TCU 63, Wyoming 55
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- TCU is a Mountain West Conference newcomer, yet
league tournaments are old hat to the Lady Frogs.

They improved to 14-2 in conference tournament games with a
63-55 win over Wyoming on Wednesday night.

The Lady Frogs (18-10) advanced to play the top-seeded and
20th-ranked BYU Cougars (24-4) in the semifinals Friday at the
Pepsi Center.

TCU won the 2001 Western Athletic Conference tourney and the
2003 and '05 Conference USA tournament championships before joining
the Mountain West Conference this school year. So, it wasn't
surprising that Frogs coach Jeff Mittie shrugged off questions
about what he felt another quality win did for his team's NCAA
tournament chances.

"My thought process on this is we want to win a Mountain West
Conference tournament championship, and so our focus is on that,"
he said. "I believe that this league has six teams that could be
deserving of a bid. Now, nobody believes we're going to get six and
I understand that. But four to five I think is reasonable.

"RPI-wise, our league is very strong. Wyoming is very deserving
of a very good look here. So I think our league is going to sit
very well at the end of this."

Natasha Lacy scored 11 of her 14 points in the second half as
TCU held off a charge by the Cowgirls, who trimmed a 17-point
first-half deficit to two points in the closing minutes.

Wyoming (20-8) got within a bucket with just under six minutes
left before Lacy sank two free throws and then added a three-point
play off a steal and layup with 1:20 left to give the Lady Frogs a
61-55 lead.

"It was kind of a backbreaker, but they're excellent shooters
and can hit a couple of 3s and get right back into it," Lacy said.

The Cowgirls had expended all their energy, though, and they
didn't have another run in them.

"I thought the steal was huge," Mittie said.

The Cowgirls shot just 3-for-25 from the field in the first half
and trailed 32-17 at halftime. They actually shot better from
beyond the arc (2-for-6) than they did inside it (1-for-19).

TCU, however, turned the ball over 20 times overall, and Wyoming
crept back into the game, pulling to 51-49 on Michelle Taylor's
driving basket with 5:43 left.

Jenna Lohse sank one of two free throws, Lacy added two more and
Vanessa Clementino swished a 3-pointer to push TCU's lead to 57-49
with just over four minutes left.

Lorie Butler-Rayford added 12 points for the Frogs and
Clementino and Adrianne Ross each scored 11.

Erin Hicks' 16 points led the Cowgirls and Megan McGuffey added
10. Hanna Zavcez scored 9 points and grabbed a career-best 15
rebounds but shot 1-for-14 from the floor and missed all five of
her 3-pointers.

Wyoming coach Joe Legerski knew his NCAA hopes took a hit with
the loss.

"You have to make it as difficult as possible on the committee.
... That means you need to win basketball games. The talk for the
last four or five weeks around Wyoming has been we've been playing
almost at tournament level for that stretch to get here. Over the
past 12 games only two teams defeated us and that's TCU and Utah,"
he said.

"Whatever is going to happen postseason wise will happen. We
just didn't make it as difficult as what we could have tonight."
